LinkItem.internal_link_text: Is your application designed to avoid approaching the scalability targets?
Do client side devices have sufficiently high bandwidth and low latency to achieve the performance needed?
Do client side devices have a high enough quality link?
Is the client application located "near" the storage account?
Are you using a CDN for content distribution?
Are you using SAS and CORS to allow direct access to storage instead of proxy?
Is your application caching data that is repeatedly used and changes rarely?
Is your application batching updates (caching them client side and then uploading in larger sets)?
Have you configured your client to use a sufficient number of concurrent connections?
Have you configured .NET to use a sufficient number of threads?
Are you using .NET 4.5 or later, which has improved garbage collection?
Have you ensured that parallelism is bounded appropriately so that you don’t overload either your client capabilities or the scalability targets?
Are you using the latest version of Microsoft provided client libraries and tools?
Are you using an exponential backoff retry policy for throttling errors and timeouts?
Is your application avoiding retries for non-retryable errors?
Is your application staying within the bandwidth or operations scalability target for a single blob?
Are you copying blobs in an efficient manner?
Are you using AzCopy for bulk copies of blobs?
Are you using Azure Import/Export to transfer very large volumes of data?
Are you storing frequently used metadata about blobs in their metadata?
When trying to upload one blob quickly, are you uploading blocks in parallel?
When trying to upload many blobs quickly, are you uploading blobs in parallel?
Are you using page blobs or block blobs when appropriate?
Are you approaching the scalability targets for entities per second?
Are you using JSON for your table requests?
Have you turned Nagle off to improve the performance of small requests?
Have you properly partitioned your data?
Are you avoiding append-only and prepend-only patterns?
Are your inserts/updates spread across many partitions?
Have you designed your schema to allow for point queries to be used in most cases, and table queries to be used sparingly?
Do your queries typically only scan and return rows that your application will use?
Are you using filtering to avoid returning entities that are not needed?
Are you using projection to avoid returning properties that are not needed?
Have you denormalized your data such that you avoid inefficient queries or multiple read requests when trying to get data?
Are you batching requests that need to be transactional or can be done at the same time to reduce round-trips?
Are you avoiding retrieving an entity just to determine whether to call insert or update?
Have you considered storing series of data that will frequently be retrieved together in a single entity as properties instead of multiple entities?
For entities that will always be retrieved together and can be written in batches (e.g. time series data), have you considered using blobs instead of tables?
Are you approaching the scalability targets for messages per second?
Have you turned Nagle off to improve the performance of small requests?
Are your messages compact to improve the performance of the queue?
Are you retrieving multiple messages in a single "Get" operation?
Are you polling frequently enough to reduce the perceived latency of your application?
Are you using UpdateMessage to store progress in processing messages, avoiding having to reprocess the entire message if an error occurs?
Are you using queues to make your entire application more scalable by keeping long-running workloads out of the critical path and scale then independently?
